n";  mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;  mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;  mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;} --> <!--[endif] --><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o:shapedefaults v:ext="edit" spidmax="1028" /> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o:shapelayout v:ext="edit"> <o:idmap v:ext="edit" data="1" /> </o:shapelayout></xml><![endif]--></p> <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span>&nbsp;</span></strong><span>&nbsp;</span><span>This project contributed both in terms of the &lsquo;intellectual merit&rsquo; and the &lsquo;broader impact&rsquo; criteria as described in NSF guidelines. The following are the outcomes of the project during the entire funding period in terms of these two criteria. </span></p> <p>This project contributed both in terms of the &lsquo;intellectual merit&rsquo; and the &lsquo;broader impact&rsquo; criteria as described in NSF guidelines. The following are the outcomes of the project during the entire funding period in terms of these two criteria.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>Intellectual Merit</strong></p> <p>The Human Genome Project has identified more than 25,000 genes in our cells. Not all of these genes are expressed at the same time or in every cell of our body. A fundamental question in gene expression is how the coordinated expression of genes is achieved during growth, development and homeostasis. Regulation of transcription occurs at multiple steps by a variety of mechanisms. The research work done under this NSF funded program has revealed that gene architecture plays a crucial role in regulating expression of a gene. A gene is a linear piece of DNA. Our research has shown that during transcription the ends of the gene physically interact with each other to form a gene loop. This loop helps in ending the transcription cycle and in coupling one round of transcription to the next transcription cycle. Furthermore, the loop provides directionality to the promoter-bound enzyme to transcribe in sense direction thereby providing directionality to the process of transcription. The research conducted under this NSF-funded grant proposal has identified the factors involved in gene looping and the molecular basis underlying regulation of transcription by gene loops. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p> <p><strong>Broader Impact</strong></p> <p>This NSF grant provided a unique educational opportunity for training students in research, particularly those from underrepresented and economically weaker groups. At least six graduate students working in the PI&rsquo;s laboratory for a PhD degree benefitted from this grant. Four of these PhD students have completed and defended their PhD theses during the duration of this project. One of these students, Scott Medler, is a local student, Nadra belongs to an under-represented minority group, while four of the six students were girls. All four students who graduated with a PhD are either teaching or continuing research at other universities.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>In addition, this grant provided training opportunities for undergraduate students. At least twenty five undergrads worked with me under &lsquo;directed study research program&rsquo; during the period of this grant. These students worked in the laboratory for at least two semesters; attended lab meetings and journal club, and presented their work in lab meeting. Out of these, ten students also performed their research within the &lsquo;Honors Thesis Program&rsquo;. Two of these undergrads, Ashley Aldea and Paul Kudla, also received authorships in publications. Katie Dwyer, another undergraduate student, is on her way to get authorship in a publication soon. Katie has also joined the lab as a graduate student. Two more undergrads are also now graduate students in different laboratories of our department. The training opportunities provided by this grant exposed these students to the intricacies of research and motivated them to contemplate a career in scientific research.</p> <p>&nbsp;</p> <p>This grant resulted in eleven research articles, four PhD theses and ten undergraduate dissertations</p><br> <p>            Last Modified: 09/02/2017<br>      Modified by: Athar&nbsp;Ansari</p> </div> <div class="porSideCol"> <div class="each-gallery"> <div class="galContent" id="gallery0"> <div class="photoCount" id="photoCount0">          Images (<span id="selectedPhoto0">1</span> of <span class="totalNumber"></span>)           </div> <div class="galControls" id="controls0"></div> <div class="galSlideshow" id="slideshow0"></div> <div class="galEmbox" id="embox"> <div class="image-title"></div> </div> </div> <div class="galNavigation" id="navigation0"> <ul class="thumbs" id="thumbs0"> <li> <a href="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398898022590_Fig.2--rgov-214x142.jpg" original="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398898022590_Fig.2--rgov-800width.jpg" title="Fig. 2"><img src="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398898022590_Fig.2--rgov-66x44.jpg" alt="Fig. 2"></a> <div class="imageCaptionContainer"> <div class="imageCaption">A gene loop. During transcription by RNAP II, the promoter and the terminator-bound factors interact to form a gene loop, which helps termination and reinitiation of transcription.</div> <div class="imageCredit">Ansari Lab</div> <div class="imageSubmitted">Athar&nbsp;Ansari</div> <div class="imageTitle">Fig. 2</div> </div> </li> <li> <a href="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398897891170_Fig.1--rgov-214x142.jpg" original="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398897891170_Fig.1--rgov-800width.jpg" title="Fig. 1"><img src="/por/images/Reports/POR/2014/1020911/1020911_10049626_1398897891170_Fig.1--rgov-66x44.jpg" alt="Fig. 1"></a> <div class="imageCaptionContainer"> <div class="imageCaption">Structure of a gene. The beginning of a gene has promoter region where transcription starts, while the end is called the terminator where transcription ends.</div> <div class="imageCredit">Ansari Lab</div> <div class="imageSubmitted">Athar&nbsp;Ansari</div> <div class="imageTitle">Fig. 1</div> </div> </li> </ul> </div> </div> </div> </div>]]></DRECONTENT>
