rovided a unique educational opportunity for training students in research, particularly those from underrepresented and economically weaker groups. At least six graduate students working in the PI’s laboratory for a PhD degree benefitted from this grant. Four of these PhD students have completed and defended their PhD theses during the duration of this project. One of these students, Scott Medler, is a local student, Nadra belongs to an under-represented minority group, while four of the six students were girls. All four students who graduated with a PhD are either teaching or continuing research at other universities.     In addition, this grant provided training opportunities for undergraduate students. At least twenty five undergrads worked with me under ‘directed study research program’ during the period of this grant. These students worked in the laboratory for at least two semesters; attended lab meetings and journal club, and presented their work in lab meeting. Out of these, ten students also performed their research within the ‘Honors Thesis Program’. Two of these undergrads, Ashley Aldea and Paul Kudla, also received authorships in publications. Katie Dwyer, another undergraduate student, is on her way to get authorship in a publication soon. Katie has also joined the lab as a graduate student. Two more undergrads are also now graduate students in different laboratories of our department. The training opportunities provided by this grant exposed these students to the intricacies of research and motivated them to contemplate a career in scientific research.     This grant resulted in eleven research articles, four PhD theses and ten undergraduate dissertations       Last Modified: 09/02/2017       Submitted by: Athar Ansari]]></POR_COPY_TXT>
